# UMICODE Specification

**Version:** 0.1 (Draft)

**Status:** Working specification

---

# 1. Purpose

UMICODE is an open-source software framework for the design, optimisation, simulation and decoding of duplex Unique Molecular Identifier (UMI) systems for long-read sequencing.

The initial application is ultra-sensitive detection of minimal residual disease (MRD) in childhood acute lymphoblastic leukaemia (ALL) using Oxford Nanopore Technologies (ONT) sequencing of immunoglobulin (Ig) and T-cell receptor (TCR) rearrangements following capture-based enrichment.

This document defines the scientific and engineering requirements of the software. It is intended to serve as the primary design specification from which all implementations will be developed.

---

# 2. Biological Motivation

Minimal residual disease is one of the strongest prognostic markers in childhood ALL. Existing molecular assays frequently rely on PCR amplification of patient-specific Ig/TCR rearrangements. While highly sensitive, PCR-based approaches may introduce amplification bias and provide only limited opportunity to inspect the complete rearranged molecule.

Long-read sequencing offers several potential advantages:

* sequencing of substantially longer VDJ fragments;
* direct inspection of the rearranged sequence;
* improved investigation of unexpected or ambiguous molecular findings;
* future compatibility with increasingly long sequencing reads.

The assay under development combines:

* duplex molecular identifiers attached prior to amplification;
* capture-based enrichment using consensus probes located adjacent to J-region sequences;
* Oxford Nanopore sequencing.

The purpose of UMICODE is to design molecular identifiers specifically for this assay.

---

# 3. Scope

UMICODE is a general framework for designing and decoding molecular codebooks under realistic sequencing error models. The initial implementation is optimised for ONT-based Ig/TCR MRD in childhood ALL, but the architecture is intended to support other assays, sequencing platforms and molecular targets.


Version 1 of UMICODE is designed for:

* Oxford Nanopore sequencing;
* duplex UMI architecture;
* capture-based enrichment;
* Ig/TCR rearrangements for childhood ALL MRD.

---

# 4. Assay Overview

The intended laboratory workflow is:

Genomic DNA

↓

End repair / adapter ligation

↓

Duplex UMI attachment

↓

Limited amplification

↓

Hybrid capture using consensus J-region probes

↓

Post-capture amplification

↓

Oxford Nanopore sequencing

↓

UMICODE decoding

↓

Consensus molecule reconstruction

↓

VDJ assignment

↓

MRD quantification

UMICODE is responsible for molecular identifier design and decoding. It is not responsible for VDJ annotation or downstream clinical interpretation.

---

# 5. Design Philosophy

UMICODE treats molecular identifiers as an encoding and decoding problem over a noisy sequencing channel.

The software is built around the following principles:

* preserve original biological molecules wherever possible;
* minimise incorrect merging of distinct molecules;
* minimise incorrect splitting of individual molecules;
* avoid unnecessary rejection of sequencing reads;
* optimise for realistic sequencing error behaviour rather than simple sequence distance;
* maintain deterministic and reproducible behaviour.

The primary objective is accurate recovery of original molecules rather than exact recovery of barcode sequences.

---

# 6. Molecular Architecture

The initial cassette architecture comprises:

Adapter

↓

Anchor

↓

Spacer

↓

Left UMI

↓

Target molecule

↓

Right UMI

↓

Spacer

↓

Anchor

↓

Adapter

The precise adapter sequences are configurable and are not hard-coded within the software.

---

# 7. Functional Requirements

UMICODE shall provide modules for:

* candidate UMI generation;
* sequence filtering;
* anchor design;
* codebook optimisation;
* sequencing simulation;
* probabilistic decoding;
* reporting and quality assessment.

All modules shall operate from a common configuration file.

---
# 8. Design Objectives

Primary objective
Develop an ONT-aware duplex UMI framework for capture-based Ig/TCR MRD in childhood ALL.
Secondary objective
Provide a modular software architecture that can be adapted to other molecular assays with minimal changes.
Long-term objective
Develop a general framework for molecular codebook design and probabilistic decoding across sequencing technologies.

# 9. Design Constraints

The optimisation framework shall support configurable constraints including:

* UMI length;
* anchor length;
* spacer length;
* GC content;
* homopolymer limits;
* sequence complexity;
* adapter compatibility;
* secondary structure constraints;
* sequencing-channel optimisation metrics.

No parameter shall be hard-coded unless required for software operation.

---

# 10. Decoding Philosophy

UMICODE shall not assume that every observed UMI exactly matches a designed sequence.

Instead, decoding shall estimate the most probable original molecular identifier using the complete available evidence.

Potential evidence includes:

* left UMI;
* right UMI;
* anchor integrity;
* sequencing quality;
* sequencing error model.

Future versions may incorporate additional biological evidence, including VDJ consistency, provided such evidence is used only for quality assessment and not for primary molecular counting.

---

# 11. Software Architecture

The initial software modules are:

* configuration;
* candidate generation;
* filtering;
* anchor optimisation;
* codebook construction;
* sequencing simulation;
* decoder;
* reporting.

Each module shall be independently testable.

---

# 12. Validation

Performance shall initially be evaluated using simulated sequencing data.

Primary metrics include:

* molecular recovery rate;
* false merge rate;
* false split rate;
* decoder accuracy;
* computational performance.

Subsequent versions shall support optimisation using empirical sequencing data.

---

# 13. Non-goals

Version 1 of UMICODE does not aim to:

* perform VDJ annotation;
* replace established repertoire analysis software;
* discard reads solely because a UMI differs from the designed codebook;
* depend upon fixed ONT chemistries or adapter sequences.

---

# 14. Future Directions

Potential future developments include:

* empirical ONT channel modelling;
* adaptive codebook optimisation;
* support for additional sequencing platforms;
* synchronisation motifs;
* joint optimisation of complete cassette architecture;
* integration with downstream molecular quality-control workflows.

---

# 15. Guiding Principle

UMICODE exists to maximise faithful recovery of original biological molecules through the joint design of molecular codebooks and probabilistic decoders that are tailored to realistic long-read sequencing behaviour.
